  "prompt": "What is the difference between angular velocity and angular acceleration?",
  "response": "Angular velocity and angular acceleration are both concepts related to rotational motion, but they describe different aspects of that motion.\n\n1. **Angular Velocity**:\n   - **Definition**: Angular velocity is a measure of the rate at which an object rotates around a particular axis. It tells you how fast the angle is changing as the object rotates.\n   - **Units**: The standard unit for angular velocity is radians per second (rad/s), although it can also be expressed in degrees per second or revolutions per minute.\n   - **Vector Quantity**: It is a vector, meaning it has both magnitude and direction. The direction of the angular velocity vector is along the axis of rotation, following the right-hand rule.\n\n2. **Angular Acceleration**:\n   - **Definition**: Angular acceleration is a measure of the rate at which the angular velocity of an object changes with respect to time. It tells you how the rotational speed is increasing or decreasing.\n   - **Units**: The standard unit for angular acceleration is radians per second squared (rad/s\u00b2).\n   - **Vector Quantity**: Like angular velocity, angular acceleration is also a vector. Its direction can be determined based on the change in angular velocity, following the right-hand rule.\n\nIn summary, while angular velocity describes how quickly an object rotates, angular acceleration describes how quickly the angular velocity itself is changing.",
